                            <comment id="58460" author="ulsa" created="Sat, 25 Sep 2010 12:38:18 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not convinced that it&apos;s as simple as you suggest. The return value null indicates that, as for the underlying Hashtable, that the attribute with the specified name could not be found. In the case you describe, the attribute was actually found, but it had no values. Treating these cases equally may have larger impact.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For example, there is a property &quot;java.naming.ldap.typesOnly&quot; that is used to get only the names and no values. Wouldn&apos;t this fix render all those results invalid? I don&apos;t know yet, but it probably needs to be investigated.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="58464" author="ulsa" created="Sat, 25 Sep 2010 14:23:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Ah, I see it now. It will fail on the oneAttr.get() call regardless, since it does a size() check itself. You&apos;re right.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
